Deputy President William Ruto&rsquo;s shoot-to-kill order to tackle bandits in Kerio Valley has been heavily criticised by the NASA leaders and other politicians in Rift Valley region.Wiper leader Kalonzo Musyoka and Ford Kenya&rsquo;s Moses Wetang&rsquo;ula said the order is unconstitutional and can be misused by security forces. Kanu politicians, led by chairman Gideon Moi, have urged Ruto not to issue careless orders and instead deal with security matters according to the law.The NASA leaders, who spoke at a rally in Eldoret on Saturday, urged the government to deal with well-known criminals instead of issuing a blanket and dangerous. &ldquo;Nowhere in the Constitution shoot-to-kill orders are allowed. Such an order is unacceptable,&rdquo; Kalonzo said. Wetang&rsquo;ula said the clashes in Baringo are an indication of Jubilee&rsquo;s failures. &ldquo;That is why we want Jubilee out because they have shown us how not to govern a country,&rdquo; he said.Speaking in Baringo on Friday, Ruto said people who attack women and children with guns should be shot dead. The DP&rsquo;s meeting was disrupted by gunfire.